5) Genetic Algorithms\
    a) 8-queens problem: Possible solutions include all the positions of each of the 8 queens on a chessboard. \
	The \'91best\'92 solution is one where no queen lies on the horizontal, vertical, or diagonal line of another queen.\
    b) Each chromosome represents a column on the chessboard, and the value of each chromosome is the row\
	number. Because any viable solution to the 8-queens problem will not have more than one queen in a \
	single column, this method of encoding minimizes the need for separate chromosomes for every row/column \
	combination. \
    c) Choose the parents randomly as a function of their fitness, so that those with better fitness are more likely \
	to be picked. For example, with Roulette Wheel selection, each individual\'92s fitness is normalized to a value \
	between 0 and 1, and a random number between 0 and 1 is chosen as the parent. \
    d)  Crossover: Choose a point in the chromosome, and form the child from the part of the chromosome before	the crossover point of one parent and the other side of the crossover point of the other parent.\
	Mutation: randomly change some of the values of the child\'92s chromosomes, at a low probability.\
    e)  Elitism: Provides the benefits of not losing uniquely fit individuals (for instance, if a very specific combination \
	of chromosomes provides the solution), but at the cost of reducing the speed at which a population improves \
	(especially if the \'91best\'92 individuals at a given point are no where near the ideal fitness level).\
\
